{"parse":{"title":"Speculum Britanniae","pageid":23279416,"revid":679062763,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg/220px-Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"153\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg/330px-Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg/440px-Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1293\" data-file-height=\"902\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Map_of_south_essex_1594_John_Norden.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Norden's map of south Essex from the <i>Speculum Britanniae</i></div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>Speculum Britanniae</b></i> (\"Mirror of Britain\"), published in London from 1593, was a projected, but unfinished, <a href=\"/wiki/Chorography\" title=\"Chorography\">chorography</a> of Britain by <a href=\"/wiki/John_Norden\" title=\"John Norden\">John Norden</a> (1548\u20141625).<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It was intended to take the form of a series of county maps, accompanied by place-by-place written descriptions. Norden was primarily a surveyor and <a href=\"/wiki/Cartographer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cartographer\">cartographer</a>, and the written descriptions always had a subsidiary role, being much slighter than other early <a href=\"/wiki/English_county_histories\" title=\"English county histories\">county histories</a>. Nevertheless, they were based on direct observation, and Norden recorded much topographical and antiquarian detail of interest, including the <a href=\"/wiki/Heraldry\" title=\"Heraldry\">heraldry</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/English_church_monuments\" title=\"English church monuments\">tombs</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Archaeological_site\" title=\"Archaeological site\">archaeological sites</a>.\n</p><p>The first instalment, <i>Speculum Britanniae: the First Parte: an Historicall, &amp; Chorographicall Discription of Middlesex</i>, was published in 1593. The second, <i>Speculi Britaniae Pars: the Description of Hartfordshire</i>, appeared in 1598. In 1595 Norden wrote a \"Chorographical Description\" of <a href=\"/wiki/Middlesex\" title=\"Middlesex\">Middlesex</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Essex\" title=\"Essex\">Essex</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Surrey\" title=\"Surrey\">Surrey</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sussex\" title=\"Sussex\">Sussex</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hampshire\" title=\"Hampshire\">Hampshire</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Wight\" title=\"Wight\">Wight</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Guernsey\" title=\"Guernsey\">Guernsey</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Jersey\" title=\"Jersey\">Jersey</a>, as a presentation manuscript for Queen Elizabeth (now British Library Add. MS 21853), but it remained unpublished. (He did, however, publish maps alone of Surrey, Hampshire, Sussex and probably Kent.) In 1596 he published an explanation and justification of the overall project as <i>Speculum Britanniae: a Preparative to this Work</i>. In 1604, he presented to James I a more expansive description and set of nine maps of <a href=\"/wiki/Cornwall\" title=\"Cornwall\">Cornwall</a> (later published in 1728). A description of Northamptonshire (which he had surveyed in the 1590s, and is known to have completed in 1610) reached print in 1720; and one of Essex (related to, but distinct from, that in the \"Chorographical Description\") was eventually published in 1840.\n</p><p>The idea of a work that was a \"mirror\" of a land or even of a region of thought had given rise to an extensive medieval \"<a href=\"/wiki/Mirror_literature\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mirror literature\">mirror literature</a>\".\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Speculum_Britanniae&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">S.G. Mendyk, <i>Speculum Britanniae: regional study, antiquarianism, and science in Britain to 1700</i>, 1989.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2164\nCached time: 20180916034407\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.040 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.052 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 100/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 341/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 83/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 397/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.008/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 670 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   35.668      1 -total\n 67.94%   24.232      1 Template:Italic_title\n 27.50%    9.807      1 Template:Reflist\n  7.72%    2.753      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:23279416-0!canonical and timestamp 20180916034407 and revision id 679062763\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"ar","url":"https://ar.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D9%85%D9%86%D8%B8%D8%A7%D8%B1_%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B7%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7","langname":"Arabic","autonym":"\